2016231.self_intro:
Hello All, 

I am probably a bit old, although I recently stayed in a hostel. I compare this to the Airbnb experience, and I ask myself  - why would you stay in a hostel? For the same price or better you can have an apartment or large room and access to all the conveniences.  I can appreciate the need to talk to exotic boys and girls, but Airbnb is better...

Why would you stay in a hotel for that matter? I can apreciate the need to flood a bathroom every now and then, but Airbnb is better....

Me..

The place I found most interesting on my travels was Detroit  - a city in the richest nation on earth in ruins. A good place to trespass empty office towers and trade scrap metal. I have been to a few more places also. 

In future I would like to visit all the Metro/Underground networks in the former Soviet Union and also take the ferry from Aberdeen to Shetland to Orkney to Faeroe to Iceland. 

I listen to all types of music from country to techno, continuum exclusive of pop. 

I also like all sports and exercise and I enjoy recreational reading. I am reading 'In Cold Blood' now and I think my favorite book is Catch 22. I like non fiction topics like law, society, economics and history. I also like movies and shows that are not trivial. 

I would like have a beer with the Polish women's indoor volley ball team. 

I look forward to meeting you all...
2016231.name: Sam

186720515.self_intro:
Friendly and considerate man with a disability which does affect my accomodation options. I understand that it may not be possible for some locations to be made safe for me and also understand the difficulty that may involve in order to accomodate me. I have an illness known as Multiple Chemical Sensitivity (MCS) which basically means that I suffer from adverse reactions when exposed to petro chemical, volatile organic compounds, the most prolific of these is FRAGRANCE. The sheer ubiquity of these chemicals upon the majority of people means the enter the outside world I need to wear a mask. I need to stay in accomodation that has clean airflow and is able to be cleaned with water and vinegar prior to arrival. This will make for a more relaxed healthy stay for myself and is very much appreciated. In addition it is important to not provide complimentary toiletries unless FRAGRANCE free. I would normally bring my own bed clothes as these are usually washed in detergent containing FRAGRANCE, unless such washing is done in FRAGRANCE free detergents.

I have been disabled with this difficult condition for 8 years now and have grown accustomed to managing a life that needs to be protected from the chemicals contained in FRAGRANCE. Whilst I certainly do not wish anyone who wears personal hygiene products containing FRAGRANCE ill will I do encourage people to think about the compounds next to on or upon the skin that contain a myriad of untested chemicals. The easiest way to lessen ones chemical load is to switch to FRAGRANCE free detergents. 

I previously worked with general practitioners on Population Health programs and initiatives through the Federal department of health. I now live in the remote countryside after many years of living in Sydney. I have a beloved dog called Ketu and a dedicated and loving care person and feel rather fortunate in this respect.

Hello! My name is Jack and im from Newcastle, Australia! Ive spent my whole life growing up around Newcastle and (hopefully) in the near future I plan on travelling the world, meeting new people and basking in a realm of new experiences and cultures. Ive so far grasped a small amount of Europe and Asia but as time goes I definitely plan on experiencing more and more countries!

Im an incredibly considerate guy, I love helping people and making everyone as comfortable as I can. I tend to rely on my sense of humour alot when meeting new people, even if its as painfully awful as it is. 
Music is a very strong passion of mine and has been throughout my adolescence. My father was in a band whilst I was in my younger years, which means ive been surrounded by various types of music almost my entire life. im entirely open minded about music and I can almost listen to any genre under the sun and appreciate it. It can go from listening to Ariana grande, to an experimental noise rock or noise rap band. I also know how to play the guitar, drums, piano and have taught myself independently how to produce my own music through a music software called ableton. 
Sports is a huge passion of mine also, and can stay on that topic for hours. My favourite sports are Basketball (Milwaukee Bucks) , Soccer (Newcastle Jets) and American Football (Cleveland Browns) but I also have an appreciation towards League, AFL, Baseball and Ice Hockey!
As a traveller I am very neat and tidy. Id hate to be invited into someones home im not familiar with and have my clothes and other things scattered around their home as its incredibly rude and disrespectful. Im incredibly considerate of all things inside the household, whether it is furniture, artworks, beliefs etc and will not cause a problem. 

So thats me in a pretty short passage. if you have a question or request PLEASE feel free to message me and I will have no problem getting back to you. Thank you very much for reading and getting to know me a little bit better!!
252477461.name: Jack

25023479.self_intro:
We are a couple from Australia and Argentina, who met whilst travelling in the north of Mexico in the state of Sinaloa on a passenger train, named El Chepe. Sofi embarked the journey by herself, while Mitch arrived with two friends (later named Los Gueros). We all became friends on the train after sharing similar interests and later we changed our plans to all hang out together in a small town called Creel. Here is where all of our travelling began. 

After two weeks Sofi had to return to Argentina, however we kept messaging and speaking over two months. We both realised that we wanted to see each other again so she retured to Guadalajara, Mexico, where Mitch was studying. After Mitch´s time in Guadalajara he travelled to Argentina to celebrate the end of her studies.

Following this, Sofi sold all her things, quit her job, and moved to Madrid to be with Mitch, where he is currently studying.

We are now travelling around the world. Together we have already summed 20 countries in 4 continents over the last year.

We travel light, with just a guitar, an ukelele, mate (typical argentinian) and an attitude for every situation and experience, ¨all for the story not the glory¨.

We are both fluent in each others languages and speak a mix of Spanish/English with Mexican, Australian, and Argentinian slang.

I am Thomas. I was born in the Caribbean Islands, in Martinique which is part of France's overseas territories. I moved quite a lot during my childhood in mainland France and overseas. Now I am a grown-up I keep on this trend. I have lived one year and a half in Madison (WI) but also stayed briefly in Japan. After finishing my PhD in Paris (I work on understanding better sleep, dreams and consciousness), I spent one year traveling across Africa and South America with my wife and Béchamel, our faithful Land Rover Defender. 45,000km of fun!
As you can see from this brief description, I love traveling. And I love traveling in the most possible different ways. AirBnB is one of these ways. I love the possibility of escaping  touristic zones to find yourself chatting and laughing with somebody in the middle of a residential area. It gives you a different insight on how is life there.
When I am not traveling, I escape the daily routine with music and reading. I like to fool myself thinking I can play harmonica. As for work, I have embarked this great modern adventure which consists in trying to understand the brain.

I've been lucky enough to do a decent amount of travelling in my life so far. Next on the wish list would include Iceland, and Croatia. I also wouldn't say no to relaxing on a cruise through the Mediterranean.

Food is one of the best parts about travelling. It's a fun way to connect with the local culture. I love to save money on things like accommodation and transport so that I can spend a little more on things like food and activities.

I enjoy both travelling with friends and family and also travelling alone. I lived in Canada on a working holiday VISA for three years and had the time of my life. It was a great way to gain independence and meet a tonne of new awesome people.

I can't wait to keep exploring.

59060718.self_intro:
Born in Africa, we are a husband-and-wife team with Dutch-French ancestry. 
We lived in Southern Africa (Cape Town & Johannesburg), France (Paris) and Australia (Sydney & Hunter Valley).
We enjoy sharing Thulanathi with people.  Thulanathi gives visitors the opportunity to experience an authentic Australian farm with nature, fine architecture, beautiful garden and the great qualities offered by the Hunter Valley Region.  It is a real haven for family, friends, guests and wildlife.
We searched the world for our next chapter and found this gem in Pokolbin, only 90 minutes north of Sydney.
During our travels we visited great places and met awesome people in Europe, Asia, Australia, New Zealand, North & South Americas, Islands of the Pacific and Africa. 
We normally travel for business, health, education and to celebrate important milestones in life. 
We still prefer independent and small group travel arrangements to enjoy safe and close experiences with locals - that being people and nature".
Stephan organises and often guides 4WD safaris, road trips, mountain & bush hikes and opportunities for nature conservation, observation & interpretation. Karen loves learning, tea, painting and reading.

My husband and I enjoy travelling.  We have a caravan and have traveled extensively throughout Australia with it as our home.  Additionally, we enjoy catching up with friends and family on short trips where we have increasingly used AirBNB properties because of location, charm and friendly hosts!  
An overseas trip is being planned for 2018.  The first part will be with my sister, Joy, and our nieces Gemma and Ella.  We will be spending time in England and France where we will be joined by Ron before they fly home and Ron and I have time in France and Italy before joining a cruise of the Mediterranean.  Exciting times ahead!  
On longer holidays we love to stay in one place for a time to really get to know the area and people as well as the places to eat and gather food, rather than moving every day.  That way we make where we stay our home and treat it as we would our own.

Hi From Belinda and Tony,
We would love to share with you our small piece of paradise. After a career in childcare and horticulture, raising a family and having travel adventures in Australia, Europe, Asia, America and Africa, we have found the idilic Elands. I am still working a few hours helping out at our tiny local school. My other passion is patchwork and quilting.  We spend our time growing strawberries and developing an orchard of heritage cider apples and hazelnuts. Also starting a small flock of miniature sheep to be our grass powered lawn mowers. 5571854.self_intro:
This is my half of the profile. I'm a yoga instructor with a passion for essential oils and all things botanical. I walk lots, swim in creeks whenever I get the chance and play a couple of instruments in my downtime (which is infrequent unfortunately). 

My partner and best friend - Dan - is an illustrator and designer who has worked for a major Australian newspaper for nearly 20 years. He now works from home where he gets to hang out with our fur babies all day. Dan plays music too (he's a much better musician than me) and we love playing together. 

We own a historic commercial building in a quaint country town which operates as a pop-up vintage store. Collecting is a shared obsession that eats all our spare time and change. Neither of us smoke, we have two rescue cats, Lizzie and Molly, no kids and love serenity. 

We're not exactly 'frequent flyers' but like the thought of getting out and about once in a while, and traveling always means a road trip. For us it all comes down to nature worship of a kind... so we're always mindful of our impact on the environment (and yours too).

Hi,

I'm a professional in my 30's

I have a 2 bedroom art deco flat in Waverley and am looking to rent out a spare room on a casual basis over the Summer. The spare room comes furnished with a really good quality queen sized bed [I can also provide another spring coil single mattress]

The room is very large in size (5x5 metres), has high ceilings, wooden floors and antique/vintage style furniture  (drawer, cabinet and coffee table). It faces East, and and gets a lot of natural sunlight. It has a large balcony with four outdoor chairs that people could use at the same time, while soaking up the morning sun or having a reprieve from the heat in the afternoon, when there is a nice cool breeze.

The location is great. Bondi Junction shopping centre is a couple of blocks away (5 minutes walk). Bronte beach and Tamarama are down the road (about 10-15 minutes respectively), Bondi beach is also nearby (approx. 20 minutes). 

The kitchen and bathroom facilities are functional and clean and tidy, but are fairly basic so please be aware that they are lacking the Miele ovens and Swedish tap faucets;) 

The room costs $80 a night for one to two people. Drop me a line if you are interested.

Cheers
Evan

1640934.self_intro:
I am a Visual Artist with a Visual Arts Degree majoring in Jewellery Design & Making and Photography.  
My husband is a clever, hard-working person who has obtained his Bachelor's degree (triple major in Modern History, International Relations and Politics)  as well as his Master's degree (International Law and International Relations) whilst working full-time.  

When we aren't travelling, we live in a suburb of Adelaide called Hallett Cove. Our property is adjacent to the Hallett Cove Conservation Park which holds some of Australia's most outstanding geographical and archeological sites and is rated as one of the top 5 coastal walking trails in Australia.

I love to acquire new skills and these have included professional cookery, hairdressing and make-up artistry which was my segue to photography and  my Visual Arts Degree.
Cooking still remains a passion of mine: Mediterranean, Middle Eastern, Asian/Chinese-Sichuan with the typical Australian fusion approach to these food styles. 
Other interest include collecting  vintage cameras, Mid Century Sklo Union glass, and anything Art Deco and Mid-Century Modern.

We have planned a marathon of travel over the next few years. A trip to the UK eventuated in May-July 2018 as well as a return trip to Brooklyn later in the year.  2019 has been a year of interstate travel to Mandurah, WA as well as Melbourne, Torquay and Jan Juc.  A week-long trip to a resort in Nusa Dua was our introduction to Bali and 3 weeks in Germany at the Christmas and New Year period will complete travel for the year.
Airbnb is a fantastic way of spending time in a city and gaining insight as to how other people live and spend their time.  Spending time in other cities/countries has given me a new-found appreciation of my own life here in Australia.
We are quiet, clean and tidy non-smoking guests and like to leave our lodgings in an immaculate state. We understand the concept of respecting others and their possessions/abode as we would like to be treated.
1640934.name: Susi

We both love people and sharing our wisdom & knowledge.  I am a professional Life Coach and Bars Facilitator and have been assisting and guiding people for many year.  
I enjoy the beach  both summer and winter.  At every opportunity especially in the cooler months, both Mario and I enjoy going to Peninsula Hot Springs in Rye.
I love experiencing other cultures and listening to different accents.
We have been to India many times as it feeds my soul and in turn bring that back to infuses others.  We also assist an orphanage in Mysore.

We love to travel, especially Italy as Mario has family living in Tuscany.  And we both speak italian.

I love a great film, especially if based on or inspired by true life happenings.  Mario also loves, loves action films.

We both love good quality food, simply cooked.   One of our favourite ingredient is a really good olive oil.

As for Baringa Villa.
When friends or guest stay they all comment on the tranquility of the place and how they could just sit, linger, and enjoy the peace and calm.
Given that our home is now bigger than we required!   And that we were able to easily create the private space,  Baringa Villa was born.

We really look forwards to your stay with us!

My favourite place in the world (so far) would have to be Iceland - I spent four weeks volunteering there and loved every minute. 

I'm a (recently graduated) urban planner by day, so am very interested in how cities function and feel. In my spare time I volunteer with an NFP organisation that arranges volunteer placements for Australians overseas - spreading the word about travel and volunteering! I also enjoy a good knit and sewing session, and of course hanging with friends and exploring my lovely city of Melbourne.

I met my wife and we spent the early days of our relationship in that unit, on the beach and in the water.  We have been married for 3 years now and we have a growing family.
 
We return to Makaha as often as possible.  Nothing changes.  The sunsets are magical, the beach is calming and soothing.  The locals still greet you with a big smile and Aloha!
 
If you are into surfing, diving, snorkeling, or just relaxing under coconut palm with a good book, this place is for you.  

Aloha,

Rob and Paula Murray

11462830.self_intro:
I am retired travelling Grey Nomad 69yo [without a Winnebago] who divides his time between travelling overseas and in Australia, involvement in various volunteer projects and also doing house sits.

Reviews

I am male, ex teacher, university trained, Justice of the Peace and avid traveller.

I was travelling through Morocco and Western Europe after spending time in the Middle East and Eastern Europe in 2017/2018.
My previous trip was to Taiwan where I enjoyed the unique Japanese-Chinese style cooking and the wonderful scenery of this wonderful country.
I am not the typical senior citizen as I don't like to play bingo, hang around RSLs, and lead a quiet life. 
I like to be out there riding on the Yangon to Mandalay train, up close and personal to orang-utangs in Borneo or sitting in Petaling St in KL at my favourite satay stand.

CURRENT MISSION
Just to live every day with honesty and integrity

ABOUT ME
Kind, generous, talkative, reflective, analytical, philosophical,humanitarian and spiritual

PHILOSOPHY

"Follow your Bliss" (Joseph Campbell)

"Ships are safe in harbours but that's not what ships are made for" (John Shedd)

"Even a stab in the back is a step forward" (Gabe)

"All truth passes through three stages. First it is ridiculed. Second it is violently opposed. Third it is accepted as self evident" (Schopenhauer)

"A comfort zone is a beautiful place but nothing grows there"(unknown)

"Be the change you want to see in the world" (Gandhi)

INTERESTS
Travel, travel, travel 
Aussie Rules Football- Carn the Hawks!!! 
Playing music-beginner guitar and piano 
Swimming in waterholes and gorges 
Taking photos with my little Canon point and shoot 
Humanitarian projects- Kiva ( a global microfinance lending organisation), and Watsi (a world wide donation site for those in medical need).

MUSIC, MOVIES & BOOKS
Music: 
Backsliders
Fred Smith- Canberra singer and songwriter 
John Butler Trio 
Spooky Men's Chorale 
Ani DiFranco 
Jeff Lang 
Kate Miller-Heidke

Movies: 
Harold and Maude 
Chocolat 
Dead Poet's Society 
Paris Texas 
Green Fried Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe 
Indiana Jones trilogy 
Out of Africa

Books: 
Knulp-Hermann Hesse 
The Bridge Across Forever-Richard Bach 
The Bridges of Madison County-R J Waller 
Any Lonely Planet Travel Guide 
The Prophet- Kahlil Gibran

ELEVEN AMAZING THINGS I'VE DONE

Walked in the Himalayas- 20 days mainly solo-no porters or sherpas

Slept on a boat in the middle of Halong Bay Vietnam amid all the towering limestone hill rising out of the sea.

Rode on top of a petrol tanker near Katmandu (Nepal)on a wonderful mountain road

Met Amma(the hugging mother guru)at her ashram in Kerala (India) and got one of her famous hugs.

Met the Sultan of Brunei and received a gift to commemorate the occasion.

Babysat a 2 yo girl(Rachel) and 4 yo girl(Justine) for 2 weeks while their mother was absent. Hardest job I've ever had

Flew from a mountain ledge from Jomsom to Pokkara in the Himalayas on a STOL Nomad aircraft-scary

Travelled on the famous Yangon to Mandalay express train in Myanmar.

Hitchhiked across America, through Europe and around Australia.

Trekked through Borneo jungles in Sarawak and Sabah

Hiked Tiger Leaping Gorge in Yunnan (China)

Led 10x canoe/camping expeditions down the Wapsipinicon River in Iowa USA with 30 kids as part of my Camp Counseling duties at a YMCA summer camp.

 In 2017/8, I spent 352 days travelling through four continents, 21 countries, 49,496 km covered. Took 10,843 photos on my iP5 and Canon SX 260

TEACH, LEARN, SHARE

We are all catalysts for each other. And everybody is my teacher

WHAT I CAN SHARE WITH HOSTS
Sense of humour 
Lots of travel stories 
Some photos

COUNTRIES I'VE VISITED
Armenia, Austria, Belgium, Bosnia, Brunei, Bulgaria, Cambodia, Canada, Czech Rep, China, Croatia, Egypt, England, Georgia, Germany, Greece, Hungary,  India, Indonesia, Iran, Israel, Laos, Liechtenstein, Macedonia, Malaysia, Morocco, Myanmar, Netherlands, New Zealand, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Serbia, Singapore, Slovakia, Switzerland, Taiwan, Thailand, Turkey, Viet Nam

COUNTRIES I'VE LIVED IN
Australia, New Zealand, United States

10937394.self_intro:
Hello - we are Robyn and Bruce, a semi-retired professional couple, who enjoy travel and meeting people! We have met some great house guests from regional Victoria, interstate and overseas and enjoy traveling ourselves with AirBnB.  

We joined Air BnB in early 2014 initially with our Melbourne apartment, then in March 2016 listed our renovated beach home at Anglesea on the beautiful Great Ocean Road.  Our focus in hosting is comfort and meeting your needs for a relaxed holiday.  It is now our principle place of residence and more of a family home that we share for special guests. 

The drive is 1.5+ hours from Melbourne to Anglesea on the beautiful Great Ocean Road.  We've renovated our 80s home with modern bathrooms and laundry, fully equipped kitchen and a wonderful living environment inside and outside.   Anglesea is on a pretty river that runs through the town to the spectacular Surf Beach.  Another beach more suitable for families is at Point Roadknight.  It's a 15-20 minute walk to the main beach, surf club and shops or 5 mins by car.

Our home adjoins the 18th Fairway of the famous Anglesea Golf Course with its many kangaroos and bird life!  If you love photography and walks, surfing and swimming, come and enjoy our sanctuary.  We've 2 lovely balconies for just chilling out with a drink or a good book and an outdoor Balinese shower complete with hot water! Jenny and Neil have 7 children, and one grandchild who lives in Germany. They also have chickens and a small friendly dog on their property.  In their free time they enjoy bushwalking, kyaking and exploring new places.  They also enjoy eating out at the various restaurants and cafes in the area and perusing the art galleries and antique shops in the Mountains.

Jenny and Neil completed building Maple Cottage in late 2017 and opened it up to air bnb travellers in early 2018.  They love living in the Blue Mountains National Park, where they are surrounded by wildlife, fresh mountain air and magestic views. Their dream is to provide comfortable modern accommodation to travellers from all over the world and a home away from home for couples who desire an escape from their every day environment and lifestyle.

Busy, gregarious professional who often travels for work and leisure. Relaxed, friendly and down to earth, I like to share my home with friendly, positive, independent people who are keen to explore Sydney or just enjoy a relaxing trip away from home. I have extensively travelled so have filled the unit with treasures and photos from my many travels. Eclectic but tidy, I welcome anyone looking for a warm, inviting, friendly and stylish place to stay in Sydney. I'm an Aussie female from Sydney. I love to travel but what I really look forward to is immersing myself into a place rather than passing through for a few days. I love tasting local flavours (I LOVE food!), shopping in local boutiques, and rummaging in local markets. I like to be comfortable and clean and independant when I travel, so hostels aren't for me. And while I can certainly be happy lapping in luxury, I crave authenticity and find resorts and glitzy hotels so impersonal and generic. 

I love South American culture, literature, music and dance - sometimes I think I must have been latin in a previous life - so I tend to find local salsa spots in every major city I travel to. It's a great way to meet locals and connect, even if I don't speak the language. 

As a person, I'm honest, reliable and trustworthy. I'm clean, tidy and conscientious. I'm really very excited about joining this Airbnb community, where have you been all my life?! 

If there's anything else you'd like to know about me, please only ask! 

x Mika :-)

Hi there!

My name is Mark Miranda, a new Airbnb host. I have a complicated relationship with my partner who lives in the next town and I stay there often. I have two beautiful daughters named Isabella and Milena. 

I travel a lot for work and my apartment is constantly empty hence why I have chosen to use Airbnb to rent out my whole minimise apartment except for my room. My apartment is like living in a resort and close to all amenities such as transport, gyms, shops, parks, etc.

I love to travel (which works well with my work as I frequently travel around Asia-Pacific), I love to read (when I get the chance), don't mind the odd binge tv series (e.g. GoT has got me!), eating out and having a general good time! I'm also into fitness in general and not a bad salsa dancer apparently.

If you have me as a host, I will share you my insights to my beautiful city and most of the time I may not be there as I'm travelling. However, if I am there, you will have a great experience sharing stories and experiences.

I'm a very independent traveller as I have been lucky enough to travel the globe on many occasions. I love learning new cultures, languages, architectures and of course meeting the people along the way which creates a unique experience.

My life motto - Happy, healthy, wealthy and wise are my motives in life!

Happy because life is so sad and bad at times, it's better to have a positive outlook in life. 

Healthy because no point feeling yucky! Treat the body like a shrine but give it a bit of a bashing every now and then to keep you in check!

Wealthy because there is so much money out there, it's not funny! I just want a small piece of the action if I can.

Wise because as we grow older, we accumulate knowledge and experience which defines who we are.

4080963.self_intro:
I am a 57 year old woman living in Australia with my husband, Graham, and a couple of spoilt cats. Sometimes the two of us travel together, and sometimes we travel separately or with other friends. The cats stay home with a standby slave.

We live on the Central Coast of NSW Australia, about an hour and a half north of Sydney where we practice and teach permaculture. We're passionate about designing systems that meet human needs while increasing ecological health. We like to tread lightly on the planet which is part of why we use Airbnb.

As guests we are friendly, quiet, clean and tidy and treat your home as our own. We clean up as we go and like to leave a place as we found it (sometimes even cleaner). We don't smoke and prefer not to be around smoking, or in premises where people smoke, so please disclose this in your listing and don't say you're non-smoking if the property hosts smokers. Seriously, no amount of air freshener will do it. We've had a couple of really unpleasant experiences in the past. It shows, doesn't it. 

We like to walk or use public transport when we travel and to see the hidden gems that locals recommend as well as the usual tourist spots, so please let us know if you have a favourite restaurant or if there's something we shouldn't miss while we're with you. We like most kinds of food, shared with good company and a nice bottle of wine so if you can leave a map marked with the nearest bottle shop and the closest good takeaway it would be greatly appreciated. 

I'm just reading the Airbnb recommendations for a profile. Does anyone really list five things they can't live without? Or their favourite movies? Or their life motto??Happy to share this information when we meet if it's important to you. I'm guessing not. 

I understand that inviting strangers into your home can be at least a little stressful, so please read my reviews. Of course I'm going to say nice things about myself. It's what other hosts say that matters.
4080963.name: Meg

I am a mother of three children that loves to lead an active life. With my husband Peter we try to swim down at the beach as much as possible. Summer starts in Newport sometime in September and we try to get our swimming season to last at least until April.  In the Winter months it is a bit too cold to get in the water without a wet suit so we will take our little dog Neville along the Ocean paths to watch for whales and dolphins. 
Newport is a village where everyone knows everyone either through the surf club, schools or our many sporting groups. A stroll down to one of Newport's many cafes can take some time as we run into people and catch up. Five minutes walk from our place is the fabulous Newport Arms Hotel. It is a great place to watch the sun go down over Pittwater or listen to live music on a Sunday afternoon. Life is good. Come and see!
Life's motto......Jump In.

103519678.self_intro:
Experienced and formally trained museum guide, former school teacher (K-12, Special Ed and ESL), trained conservator, sometime optical dispenser, barista and had my fair share of work in hospitality. Oh, and I’m also curatorially and events management trained. Well versed in Australian colonial history, lover of heritage/contemporary architecture and early-mid 20th Century design.
Keen gardener, amateur cook and love to travel by plane, train and tram, on my bicycle(s) and the number 11 bus (on foot).
Impeccably clean and neat guest. Conversationalist and quite social but do not overstep. I run the gamut of helpful to a bit generous as a guest (shall I bake some scones?). 
I am a quiet and respectful house guest, and completely autonomous. I am best left to pursue my own interests while on holiday unless I am asked to share my interests and hosts wish to tailor something specifically when requested (or I seem lost OR you’re a shameless show off when it comes to your locale like I am with Sydney!)
I would even suit a household whose members are either retired or work part time and may enjoy a slight diversion such as going out for a tea/coffee and/or stroll during my stay. For an idle hour it can be fun to see the world through different eyes.
If having a longer stay, I’m happy to walk friendly dogs/mind pets, do dishes/laundry, a spot of weeding, lawn mowing, watering, etc. in the garden, and/or contribute in other handy ways to the household, entirely depending of course on pre-arrangement. 
I travel with a minimum of stuff and fuss. I use public transport and hire cars as needed at home and also when travelling. 
I prefer hosts who are liberal-minded and/or have a live and let live philosophy on life.
Life for me is all about the golden mien: goodness, truth and beauty. Sounds kinda cheesy, but life’s made much better with those essential ingredients thrown in.
103519678.name: Samuel (Sam)

detail: Work: retired - previously a landscape designer
86744.self_intro:
I'm an Australian retired landscape designer - my husband is a retired cinematographer.  We love swimming, bushwalking, music (especially blues), photography, movies.  We enjoy cooking local produce, eating regional food and drinking local wine and good coffee; entertaining friends and meeting new people.

And of course we love to travel - sometimes alone, sometimes with our adult daughters and most often together.

We've travelled throughout Australia, in Indonesia, south-east Asia, China, USA, Europe and the UK.  

Now that travel time isn't limited by work demands we are able to spend longer in each place we visit, allowing us to get to know a neighbourhood, city and/or rural surrounds. 

Self contained studios or small apartments with cooking facilities allow us to have a base from which we can explore the local area on foot or on local transport.  Learning about local cuisine and shopping for and cooking local produce is a great bonus and something we love to do.

We own our own home and understand the time and effort it takes to make accommodation comfortable and to keep it clean and functioning well.  All accommodation we stay in is respected, kept clean and tidy and treated as a home away from home.  

As guests we like to leave accommodation as we found it - we appreciate good recommendations from our hosts!
86744.name: Shane
